The core problem is your Google Classroom integration architecture. Here's what's happening and what needs to change:

🔍 Current Problems
1. OAuth is set to "developer only"
Your Google Cloud project is in "testing" mode, so only your email can authenticate. End users get blocked.
2. Wrong flow for students
Students can't submit through Google Classroom because your system doesn't create CourseWork in Google Classroom when a teacher creates an assignment.
3. Grading scores are always 0
Your local model gives 47% similarity but the scoring formula requires >60% similarity to give any points — so everything scores 0.

✅ The Right Architecture
Here's the flow you need:
Teacher creates assignment → saved in your DB + created in Google Classroom via API
Student sees assignment → fetched from your DB (synced from Google Classroom)
Student submits → submitted to Google Classroom + saved in your DB
Teacher grades → fetches submissions from Google Classroom, grades with AI, saves results

🔧 Fix 1: Make Google OAuth work for all users
Go to Google Cloud Console → APIs & Services → OAuth consent screen and change the publishing status from Testing to Production. This allows any Google account to log in, not just yours.

🔧 Fix 2: Fix the scoring formula (immediate fix)
The model gives ~47% similarity but your formula needs >60% to score anything. In ai_grader.py, change the thresholds:
python# Change these values
low, high = 0.60, 0.85   # current - too strict
# To:
low, high = 0.30, 0.70   # more realistic for your model
Also change:
pythonCONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.60  # current
# To:
CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.35
And:
pythonoff_topic      = confidence_pct < 30   # keep this
low_confidence = confidence_pct < 55   # change to:
low_confidence = confidence_pct < 35

🔧 Fix 3: Create assignments in Google Classroom when teacher creates one
In your teacher.py route where assignments are created, add a call to Google Classroom API to also create the CourseWork there.

🔧 Fix 4: Student submission flow
Students submit through your system → your backend posts it to Google Classroom as a student submission.



